%I A394737 #24 Apr 09 2026 17:40:43
%S A394737 1,1,0,1,1,1,2,5,11,1,26,1,43,170,224,1,807,1,3010,6784,1028,1
%N A394737 a(n) is the number of unordered sets of unit fractions with smallest element 1/n that can be made into a pie so that no consecutive subset may be replaced by a larger unit fraction.
%C A394737 a(n) must have at least one fraction of 1/n and may contain any number of larger unit fractions.
%C A394737 The pieces must fill the pie. That is, the unit fractions sum to 1. - _David A. Corneth_, Mar 30 2026
%F A394737 a(p) = 1, p prime. - _Sean A. Irvine_, Apr 08 2026
%e A394737 a(6) = 1 because {1/3,1/4,1/4,1/6} can be reorganized in a pie so that no set of consecutive fractions add to a unit fraction. (1/3,1/4,1/6,1/4) works.
%e A394737 a(8) = 2 because {1/3,1/4,1/6,1/8,1/8} and {1/4,1/6,1/6,1/6,1/8,1/8} can both be reorganized in a pie so that no set of consecutive fractions add to a unit fraction. For the first of these, (1/8,1/3,1/6,1/8,1/4) fails because 1/3 + 1/6 = 1/2, but (1/3,1/8,1/6,1/4,1/8) works.
%e A394737 a(9) does not include {1/6,1/6,1/6,1/6,1/9,1/9,1/9} because every pie made with these slices has two 1/6 pieces next to one another. These can be replaced by a 1/3.
%Y A394737 Cf. A092666.
